        "id": 1079748
      },
      "writtenOn": "2016-05-18T19:44:33Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Hard coding disk path inside the object makes unit-testing non hermetic.\nIf you write a unittest that changes the advancedFeatures, you\u0027ll end up changing the developer\u0027s actual file.\n\nInstead, your object should take a path to the disk file (that defaults to this location). That way, unit-tests create a temporary file and use that as the backing file.\n\nExample: crashreporter.\n- The actual implementation should be in the C++ object (as zyy@ requested earlier) https://android.googlesource.com/platform/external/qemu/+/emu-master-dev/android/crashreport/CrashReporter.h\n- A C-friendly header provides free functions to use it from C files. https://android.googlesource.com/platform/external/qemu/+/emu-master-dev/android/crashreport/crash-handler.h\n- C++ code need not go through the free functions (it can, of course). It can use the ::get() function to get the single global instance of the object to be used (as in CrashReporter / android::base::System)\n\nNow, ::get() creates a default instance with the known default path.\nBut, unit-tests create the instances directly (perhaps by making the unittest class a friend of the implementation class) and use a temporary path for the backing file.",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 88,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 89,
        "endChar": 65
      },
      "revId": "dd04a08a7943f107d549493a5645a7880008791f",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": false
    },
